{
    "_comment": "JSON-ARRAY version of perftest_trade_etl. Same pipeline as the row lane (perftest_trade_etl.json) and the Arrow lane (perftest_trade_etl_arrow.json), but the unit of work on every edge is a plain Python list of dicts (a JSON array), NOT one message (row) and NOT a pyarrow.RecordBatch (Arrow). A stock BatchingSubscriptionNode drains many Kafka trades per cycle into ONE batch envelope {batch:[...]}; each array calculator processes the whole list in a single calculate() call, so the per-message node/queue/equality-gate overhead is amortized across the batch. Stock FlatteningPublicationNode sinks unbatch back to one message per row, so the external/broker contract is unchanged. NO Arrow: the speedup comes purely from batch amortization, not columnar vectorization - the arithmetic is still pure-Python per element, so throughput is expected to sit BETWEEN the row lane and the Arrow lane. Heterogeneous trades need no stable schema here: each element is a dict, calculators read fields with .get(key,default), and summarize projects to a fixed output shape (extra attributes fall away, exactly like the row lane; the Arrow lane instead carries them in extras_json). TOPOLOGY: linear (validate->normalize->fx->notional->fees->risk->classify->anomaly->summarize), mirroring the Arrow lane's fused chain, then fan-out to three sinks. Additive/opt-in: calculators referenced by dotted path; the engine is untouched.",
    "name": "perftest_trade_etl_array",
    "description": "Kafka -> array batch-ingest -> validate -> normalize -> FX -> notional -> fees -> risk -> classify -> anomaly -> summarize -> {file sink, kafka sink, kafka async sink}. List-of-dicts (no Arrow) high-throughput equivalent of perftest_trade_etl.",
    "version": "5.19.0",
    "start_time": null,
    "duration": null,
    "subscribers": [
        {
            "name": "trade_kafka",
            "config": {
                "source": "kafka://topic/perftest_trades",
                "bootstrap_servers": ["localhost:9092"],
                "group_id": "perftest_trade_etl_array",
                "kafka_library": "kafka-python",
                "max_depth": 2000000,
                "idle_poll_interval": 0.002,
                "_idle_note": "Deep queue so the batching ingest can drain large batches under load; latency at high rate is dominated by batch fill, not poll interval."
            }
        }
    ],
    "publishers": [
        {
            "name": "output_file",
            "config": {
                "destination": "file:///tmp/perftest/trade_etl_array_output.jsonl"
            }
        },
        {
            "name": "output_kafka",
            "config": {
                "destination": "kafka://topic/perftest_trades_enriched",
                "bootstrap_servers": ["localhost:9092"],
                "kafka_library": "kafka-python"
            }
        },
        {
            "name": "output_kafka_async",
            "config": {
                "destination": "kafka://topic/perftest_trades_enriched_async",
                "bootstrap_servers": ["localhost:9092"],
                "kafka_library": "kafka-python",
                "async_egress": true,
                "_async_note": "async_egress:true routes this publisher through the WAL-backed AsyncPublisher when egress.async.enabled=true, for async vs sync side-by-side benchmarking."
            }
        }
    ],
    "calculators": [
